{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17479082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17479082"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:19:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:19:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19192"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19192"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.44,0.13,0.08,0.31]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11926"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99638"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11926"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19192"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82019"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"423"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1664"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"8904"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27944"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34123"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44009"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99638"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his parent after they noticed a white reflection in his right eye during flash photography. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. His parent reports that he has recently started colliding with furniture on his right side.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a white pupillary reflex in the right eye and a new right convergent squint. Red reflex examination reveals asymmetry between the eyes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Visual evoked potentials","Dilated fundoscopy","Visual acuity testing","Genetic testing","Magnetic Resonance Imaging"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with concerning ophthalmological signs including a white pupillary reflex, new-onset strabismus, and apparent right-sided visual field defect. These features suggest possible retinal detachment or retinoblastoma, both of which are serious conditions requiring prompt evaluation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDilated fundoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is essential as the initial investigation as it enables direct visualisation of the retina, confirming the presence and extent of any detachment. It can also identify retinoblastoma, which typically appears as a white-yellow mass with calcifications and dilated feeding vessels. Urgent ophthalmological assessment with dilated fundoscopy is critical for differentiating between these conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVisual acuity testing\u003C/strong\u003E would be challenging to perform reliably in a three-year-old child. While it may provide information about visual function, it would not identify the specific pathology causing the white pupillary reflex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic Resonance Imaging\u003C/strong\u003E may be required if fundoscopy raises concern for retinoblastoma to assess for extraocular extension, but should not precede a thorough fundoscopic examination. If retinoblastoma is suspected after fundoscopy, urgent imaging would be the next step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVisual evoked potentials\u003C/strong\u003E can assess the integrity of the visual pathway but would not provide the immediate diagnostic information needed in this acute presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenetic testing\u003C/strong\u003E may be relevant if hereditary retinoblastoma is suspected (approximately 40% of cases are hereditary) but is not appropriate as the initial investigation for acute leukocoria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERetinoblastoma is the most common primary intraocular malignancy in children and must be excluded in any child presenting with leukocoria. Early diagnosis is crucial for preserving vision and life, as delayed diagnosis can lead to metastatic disease. Other differential diagnoses for leukocoria include Coats disease, persistent hyperplastic primary vitreous, and congenital cataracts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Leukocoria, strabismus, and visual field defects are key presenting features of retinal detachment in young children.","Dilated fundoscopy is essential for diagnosing retinal detachment and differentiating it from retinoblastoma.","Retinoblastoma is a critical differential diagnosis for leukocoria in children that requires urgent evaluation."],"references":["Kliegman RM, St. Geme JW, Blum NJ, Shah SS, Tasker RC, Wilson KM, editors. Disorders of the eye. In: Nelson Textbook of Pediatrics. 21st ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82019"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19192"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82019"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-21T16:21:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-21T16:22:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11926"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99638"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","